definition.value: Any benzoic acid carrying one or more phenolic hydroxy groups on the benzene ring.
Any benzophenone into which is substituted one or more hydroxy groups.
Any member of the class of  benzoyl-CoAs having hydroxybenzoyl as the aroyl substituent.
Any member of the class of benzyl alcohols that is a benzyl alcohol substituted by at least one hydroxy group on the benzene ring.

An alpha-hydroxy ketone in which the carbonyl group and the hydroxy group are linked by a carbon bearing one hydrogen and one organyl group. Secondary alpha-hydroxy ketones are also known as acyloins, and are formally derived from reductive coupling of two carboxylic acid groups.
Any member of the class of biphenyls that has one or more hydroxy groups attached to the benzenoid ring system.
Any compound comprising a butyric acid core carrying at least one hydroxy substituent.
Any member of the class of  butanoyl-CoAs having hydroxybutanoyl as the acyl substituent.
Any member of the class of  cinnamic acids carrying one or more hydroxy substituents.

A member of the class of phosphonic acids that is methylphosphonic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a 2-(6-amino-9H-purin-9-yl)ethoxy group. An inhibitor of HIV-1 reverse transcriptase, the bis(t-butoxycarbonyloxymethyl) ester (dipivoxil ester) prodrug is used to treat chronic hepatitis B viral infection.
Any member of the class of cyclohexanones carrying one or more hydroxy substituents.
A member of the class of flavanones that consists of flavanone with one or more hydroxy substituents.
Any flavone in which one or more ring hydrogens are replaced by hydroxy groups.
Any member of the class of  fluorenes containing a mono- or poly-substituted  fluorene ring in which at least one of the substituents is a hydroxy group.
A member of the class of  hydroxyindoles that is 1H-indole substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4.
Any kynurenamine carrying a hydroxy substituent.
Hydroxylamine, H2N-OH, and its hydrocarbyl derivatives.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of hydroxymalonic acid.
Any member of the class of  naphthalenes that is naphthalene carrying one or more hydroxy groups.
Any nitrile compound which also contains a hydroxy group.
An  aldoxime that is acetaldehyde oxime in which one of the methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a hydroxyphenyl group.
A proline derivative that is proline substituted by at least one hydroxy group.
Any member of the class of pyridines with at least one hydroxy substituent.
A hydroxy fatty acid that is ocatadecanoic acid (stearic acid) in which the aliphatic chain has been substituted by one or more hydroxy groups.
A streptomycin bearing an additional hydroxy substituent at the 5'-position (on the furanose ring)
Any member of the class of  toluenes carrying one or more hydroxy substituents.
A chlorine oxoacid with formula HOCl; a weak, unstable acid, it is the active form of chlorine in water.
A member of the class of  iduronic acids that is the major uronic acid component of the dermatan sulfate and heparin.
The hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-(imidazol-5-yl)lactic acid.
